  "description": "A permutation is an arrangement of objects in a specific order. Given the letters A, B, C, the arrangements ABC, ACB, BAC, BCA, CAB, and CBA are the six permutations. Change the order and you get a different permutation, even though the same objects are involved. The number of permutations of nn distinct objects is n!n! (n factorial): n×(n−1)×(n−2)×⋯×1n \\times (n-1) \\times (n-2) \\times \\cdots \\times 1. For 3 objects, that is 3!=63! = 6. For 10 objects, it is 10!=3,628,80010! = 3{,}628{,}800. Factorials grow explosively fast, which is why permutation-counting problems quickly become computationally expensive.\n",
  "name": "Permutation",
